During a visit to Ireland, Vice President Mike Pence discussed the trading relationship between the United States and Ireland, emphasizing the importance of expanding opportunities for American exports into Ireland. Pence also expressed the desire to negotiate a free trade agreement with both the United Kingdom and the European Union. He raised concerns about the Chinese telecommunications company Huawei and its potential threat to security in the West. Pence also addressed the issue of Brexit, stating that the United States supports the UK's decision to leave the European Union but is committed to preserving the Good Friday Agreement and avoiding any unnecessary disruption of commerce. He mentioned that negotiations for a free trade agreement between the US and the UK would begin immediately after Brexit is completed. Pence defended his decision to stay at the Trump property in Doonbeg, Ireland, stating that it was a way to connect with his family roots and celebrate the bond between the Irish and American people.